{
  "query": "How do the effects of creating short versus long flexible habitats on subtidal artificial structures compare for fish and invertebrate populations in Australia?",
  "relevant_summary": "Both short (1-50 mm) and long (>50 mm) flexible habitats created on subtidal artificial structures in Australia show mixed effects on fish and invertebrate populations. Long flexible habitats (action 3451) supported macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate species that were absent from structure surfaces without flexible habitats, and had mixed effects on fish species richness depending on fish presence when habitats were created. They supported higher combined macroalgae and invertebrate biomass (mostly mussels) compared to surfaces without habitats. Short flexible habitats (action 3450) showed mixed effects on invertebrate community composition depending on habitat density, length, and site location, but did not increase invertebrate species richness on structure surfaces. Both habitat types showed mixed effects on invertebrate and fish abundance depending on various factors including species group, survey timing, and habitat characteristics.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3451",
    "3450"
  ]
}

