{
  "query": "What are the observed outcomes of transplanting or seeding organisms onto intertidal artificial structures in Australian estuaries?",
  "relevant_summary": "Ten studies examined transplanting organisms onto intertidal artificial structures in estuaries, with seven studies in southeast Australian estuaries. Studies focused primarily on oyster transplantation and revealed mixed outcomes: transplanted oysters supported macroalgae, mobile invertebrate, non-mobile invertebrate, and fish species that were absent from structures without oysters. However, transplanting oysters had mixed effects on combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness, depending on the site and presence of grooves and small ridges on surfaces. Oyster transplantation increased mobile invertebrate species richness but did not consistently increase fish species richness or abundance. Survival of transplanted organisms varied depending on species, site conditions, and structural features - oyster survival was higher in grooves compared with ridges, though survival rates varied by site. Studies found that transplanting oysters did not increase combined macroalgae and invertebrate abundance overall, though effects varied with surface features like grooves and ridges. Transplanting oysters and/or coralline algae did not increase fish abundance or the time fish spent interacting with structure surfaces.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3472"
  ]
}

