{
  "query": "In European marine environments, how do the outcomes of creating textured surfaces on intertidal structures vary?",
  "relevant_summary": "In European marine environments, creating textured surfaces on intertidal artificial structures shows varied outcomes. Based on multiple studies conducted in the UK and Netherlands, textured surfaces (\u22641 mm) on intertidal structures demonstrated mixed effects on species richness, with results depending on the type of texture created and the specific site. Macroalgal abundance was not significantly increased by textured surfaces in two studies from the Netherlands, while invertebrate abundance showed variable responses. One UK study found that creating textured surfaces along with environmentally-sensitive material increased barnacle abundance regardless of texture type, but different textures supported different abundances. The effectiveness of surface texturing appears to be context-dependent, varying by location and species group, with some studies showing no significant increase in overall species richness or abundance. Natural rocky reef topography created on intertidal structures in UK sites also showed mixed effects on invertebrate abundance and did not consistently increase species richness. Additionally, groove habitats (1-50 mm) created alongside ridges and ledges demonstrated site-dependent effects on biodiversity, with some European locations showing increased species richness while others showed no significant changes.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3466",
    "3435",
    "3474",
    "3473"
  ]
}

