{
  "query": "To improve biodiversity on intertidal artificial structures, how do the outcomes of creating natural rocky reef topography compare to creating 'rock pools'?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, creating 'rock pools' on intertidal artificial structures appears to be more effective for biodiversity enhancement compared to creating natural rocky reef topography. Rock pools showed consistently positive results across multiple studies, with 9 out of 12 replicated controlled studies finding higher species diversity and richness in pools compared to structure surfaces without pools. Rock pools supported species that were absent from structure surfaces without pools, including macroalgae, mobile invertebrates, non-mobile invertebrates, and fish. In contrast, natural rocky reef topography showed limited biodiversity benefits, with one replicated controlled study finding no increase in combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness. The evidence for rocky reef topography was based on only two studies, which found mixed effects on species abundances and reported that limpets used shaded grooves and water-retaining depressions. While rock pools demonstrated clear biodiversity improvements with 18 studies examining their effects, rocky reef topography showed minimal measurable benefits for species richness or diversity enhancement on intertidal artificial structures.",
