{
  "query": "What are the observed effects on invertebrate abundance when using environmentally-sensitive materials on artificial marine structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies examining the use of environmentally-sensitive materials on artificial marine structures show mixed effects on invertebrate abundance. On intertidal structures, using hemp-concrete in place of standard-concrete increased mobile invertebrate species richness (Action 3469), and hemp-concrete or shell-concrete increased combined macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate abundance. However, using sandstone instead of basalt or reducing concrete pH did not increase the abundance of tubeworms, oysters, limpets, barnacles, or combined invertebrates (Action 3469). On subtidal structures, three of six replicated controlled studies found that using quarried rock instead of concrete or using ECOncreteTM with added habitats had mixed effects on non-mobile and mobile invertebrate abundance, depending on rock type, species group, and site (Action 3470). Two studies found quarried rock did not increase sponge, bryozoan, ascidian, mussel, barnacle, or Serpulid tubeworm abundance, while one found shell-concrete increased bivalve abundance (Action 3470). Three studies found ECOncreteTM with added habitats supported mobile and non-mobile invertebrate species absent from standard-concrete surfaces (Action 3470). For artificial reefs, five controlled studies found no differences in overall invertebrate abundances between different reef materials, though one found breakwaters made of oyster shell bags recruited more oysters and ribbed mussels than ReefBall breakwaters (Action 2259).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3469",
    "3470",
    "2259"
  ]
}

