  "relevant_summary": "Evidence for the effects of ceasing or altering maintenance activities on artificial marine structures is limited. For intertidal artificial structures, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of ceasing or altering maintenance activities on biodiversity. For subtidal artificial structures, two studies examined these effects. One replicated, paired sites, controlled study in the USA found that reducing cleaning frequency did not alter combined invertebrate and fish community composition, species richness, diversity, or abundance on and around structure surfaces, but did increase macroalgal abundance. The same study found no effects on transplanted oyster survival or growth. A separate replicated, randomized, controlled study in Australia found that reducing the area cleaned on subtidal artificial structures increased seahorse abundance on structure surfaces.",
