{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effectiveness of reducing the slope of marine artificial structures for biodiversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Two studies examined the effects of reducing the slope of intertidal artificial structures on biodiversity in southeast Australia. One before-and-after study reported that reducing the slope of an intertidal artificial structure, along with creating rock pools, increased the combined macroalgae, invertebrate and fish species richness on the structure. However, one replicated, controlled study found that reducing the slope of an intertidal artificial structure did not increase macroalgal abundance on structure surfaces, and also did not increase oyster or mobile invertebrate abundance on structure surfaces. No studies were found that evaluated the effects of reducing the slope of subtidal artificial structures on biodiversity.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3461",
    "3442"
  ]
}

