{
  "query": "When creating flexible habitats on subtidal artificial structures, what are the comparative effects of using short versus long materials?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies examining flexible habitat creation on subtidal artificial structures, long flexible habitats (>50 mm) generally provide greater ecological benefits than short flexible habitats (1-50 mm). Long flexible habitats support macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate or fish species that are absent from structure surfaces without flexible habitats, while short flexible habitats show mixed effects without consistently supporting additional species. Long flexible habitats also support higher combined macroalgae and invertebrate biomass than both short habitats and surfaces without flexible habitats, with deeper flexible habitats supporting higher biomass than shallower ones. Both habitat types show mixed effects on invertebrate and fish abundance depending on factors like survey timing, species groups, and site conditions. Long flexible habitats demonstrate use by seahorses, while short habitats do not consistently increase species richness.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3450",
    "3451"
  ]
}

