{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating 'rock pools' on intertidal artificial structures vary by location?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies across 18 investigations show that biodiversity outcomes from creating rock pools on intertidal artificial structures vary significantly by location and environmental conditions. Location-specific findings include: in estuaries across Australia, UK, and eastern USA, rock pools supported species absent from structure surfaces. On open coastlines in UK, Ireland, and southeast Spain, pools supported different community compositions than structure surfaces. In straits in UK and Malaysia, pools enhanced biodiversity. One study in Ireland found that wave-sheltered pools filled with sediment within two years, affecting biodiversity outcomes. Shore level and wave-exposure were found to affect community composition, with wave-sheltered locations showing different outcomes than exposed sites. In Australia, effects varied depending on shore level and site, with mixed results on macroalgal abundances and invertebrate populations based on pool depth and location. The geographic distribution of studies covered multiple continents (Australia, Europe, North America, and Asia), indicating that outcomes are influenced by local environmental conditions including wave action, sedimentation patterns, and geographic setting.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3476"
  ]
}

