  "relevant_summary": "Multiple studies provide evidence that creating depressions like pits, holes, grooves, and crevices on subtidal artificial structures can enhance biodiversity. Studies from Israel (actions 3448, 3455, 3434) found that groove and pit habitats (1-50 mm) created on subtidal structures altered macroalgae and invertebrate community composition, increased species diversity, and supported species that were absent from structures without these habitat features. Hole habitats (>50 mm) on subtidal structures (action 3434) in studies from Israel and Sweden also altered community composition and increased species richness, supporting both mobile and non-mobile invertebrate and fish species that were absent from control structures. However, for crevice habitats specifically (>50 mm), no studies were found evaluating their effects on subtidal artificial structures (action 3454). The evidence shows consistently positive effects on biodiversity enhancement through the creation of various depression types on subtidal artificial structures, with effects varying by species group and habitat type.",
